eA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gfas"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:ncolu"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipd">T: Design Magazine </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">T: Design Magazine; SECTM2</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field">NOTES ON THE CULTURE</ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Waist Land</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>For her spring men's wear collection, Miuccia Prada cinched jumpsuits at the midriff and tucked jackets into high-rise (and twice-belted) waistbands. Rick Owens sliced his pants even higher -- grandpa-high -- so that they pinched right under the ribcage, and Dior Homme showed a jacket that emulated the exaggerated, hip-jutting form of the brand's famous Bar silhouette for women, which Christian Dior introduced in 1947. Nipped waists have long represented femininity incarnate -- think of Scarlett O'Hara's famously petite Civil War-era midriff (17 inches), or the elaborate stays and busks worn by Elizabeth I, despite her claim that she had the stomach of a king. What does it say about the contemporary man that variations on the theme are now in for him?</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>At Dior, the fact that a signature piece can so easily transgress the gender divide speaks to the value of heritage. A lot of things manage to do that nowadays, true, but the male waist trend only seems like another step toward neutered androgyny. This is not a look that erases sex, but rather emphasizes it. A Barbie doll's waist comes to a near V; so does Action Man's, an ideal propagated in Ancient Greece and revived in the 19th century (when men wore their own corsets). And so the silhouette hints at a different kind of gender fluidity altogether, one based on the notion that the shapes defining the hyper-masculine and the Ã¼ber-feminine are remarkably similar. The British designer Antony Price knew as much when, in the mid-'70s, he dressed both Bryan Ferry and his girlfriend Jerry Hall in broad-shouldered and slinky-hipped ensembles that would come to symbolize glam rock itself. Grace Wales Bonner and Sarah Burton of Alexander McQueen understand it now -- both use age-old tailoring techniques to carve out severe, body-centric shapes for men and women alike.</Para><Para>Perhaps the pulled-in midsection is a reflection of international belt-tightening, as more and more nations adopt grim austerity measures. Yet self-restraint can have a sort of allure. Certainly it's a quality we're craving from our political leaders, and so maybe the wasp-waisted look is on some level oppositional, a subtle jab at the conservative fat cats.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By ALEXANDER FURY </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field">Above: the couture corset designer Gabriel Moginot in one of his designs, photographed by Armin Morbach, 2012. (PHOTOGRAPH BY ARMIN MORBACH) </Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><I